.\"=============================================================================
.Sh SUBCOMMAND FILES
Subcommands are executables stored in the
.Pa ./bin
subdirectory of
.Nm Ap s
installation location.
They can be executed without using the
.Nm
wrapper,
so both of the following invocations are equivalent:
.Bd -literal -offset 4m
.Nm Cm lint Fl -js No \&.
.Qo Pf $ Po Nm Fl p Li bin Pc Ns /lint.mjs Qc Fl -js No \&.
.Ed
.Pp
Subcommands are also useable as JavaScript libraries.
When used in this way,
their usual behaviour as executables is suppressed;
for instance,
the following script won\(cqt launch a web browser,
as would happen if the
.Xr jg-browse 1
command were executed:
.Bd -literal -offset 4m
#!/usr/bin/env node
.sp
// Prints the system's installed version of Firefox
import {find, getVersion} from "jg/bin/browse.mjs";
const path = await find("firefox");
if(!path){
	console.error("Firefox is not installed");
	process.exit(1);
}
const version = await getVersion(path);
console.log("Installed Firefox version: " + version);
.Ed
.Pp
Whether a subcommand is treated as an executable or like an ordinary library \
depends on whether its path was the script originally executed by Node.js.
Note that not every subcommand exposes a usable API this way
.Pq and by extension, is safe for importing .
Consult the appropriate man page first.
.
